<subSubSection pageId="11" pageNumber="307" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1437,1088,2015]" pageId="11" pageNumber="307">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,266,1088,1115]" pageId="11" pageNumber="307">Diagnosis</emphasis>
. This species is closest in appearance to 
<taxonomicName box="[732,819,1090,1115]" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Villa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="307" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ignea">
<emphasis box="[732,819,1090,1115]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="307">I. ignea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
based on the pale colored base of the wing but can be easily separated from it by the alula being smoky hyaline (
<figureCitation box="[807,888,1125,1151]" captionStart="FIGURES 20–21" captionStartId="15.[151,264,1055,1080]" captionTargetBox="[184,1403,417,1030]" captionTargetId="figure@15.[184,1403,417,1030]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURES 20–21. Ins, details of base of wing. 20, I. ignea; 21, I. pectorcolumbo, n. sp." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3698819" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3698819/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="307">Fig. 21</figureCitation>
) (alula orange-yellow in 
<taxonomicName box="[1171,1257,1126,1151]" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Villa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="307" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ignea">
<emphasis box="[1171,1257,1126,1151]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="307">I. ignea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
